Here‚Äôs a relatively concise but structured briefing on ITIL (the Information Technology Infrastructure Library) ‚Äî what it is, how it‚Äôs evolved, its core structure, pros & caveats ‚Äî and some suggestions for how you might use it to bring methodology and direction to your IT department.

What is ITIL?
ITIL is a framework of best practices for IT Service Management (ITSM). 
Wikipedia
+2
CIO
+2

It is not a rigid methodology or a set of prescriptive rules; rather, it offers guidance (processes, practices, principles) that can be adapted to an organization‚Äôs context. 
Simplilearn.com
+3
Wikipedia
+3
diligent.com
+3

The aim is to align IT services with business needs, deliver value, manage risk, and foster continuous improvement. 
blog.c2-itsm.com
+3
CIO
+3
atlassian.com
+3

ITIL has evolved over time; the current major version is ITIL 4 (released in 2019), which incorporates more modern practices (e.g. Agile, DevOps, Lean) and places more emphasis on value streams and flexibility. 
Advised Skills
+4
freshworks.com
